title: For Sale:  Star SuperB 1911 9mm
postcontent: This model is a 1973. It is the mid 1940's variant of the Classic Star Model B and is marked " Modelo Super " on the right hand side of the slide. This model was made from 1946 to the end of classic-model production in 1983.. The major change in the "Super Model " over the standard model B is the replacement of the swinging link with a Sig 210 (or modern Star) style closed cam path integral to the barrel. Related to this, a full-length guide rod with captive spring, and a quick take down lever were added as well. All of these models have a magazine safety, but one slightly different from the later S variants, and the extractor is modified to double as a loaded-chamber indicator. Additionally, the sights are improved in shape to make them easier to see, and minor changes were made to the trigger system. Condition on this is actually quite nice coming in at a very strong very good by surplus standards. Expect some holster / carry wear and minor scratches etc. txt REDACTED. $250

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec P32
postcontent: Very rare second generation P32 (acp) with FACTORY hard chrome finish. This gun has been fired no more than 100 times to assure reliability for carry. It weighs about 9 ounces loaded, which is about what one 1911 magazine weighs with 7 rounds of .45acp ammo!Condition is excellent and comes with all original paperwork, box, and the zippered pouch (never used or even taken out of box). It also comes with a leather Galco pocket holster that is a perfect fit. The holster is actually virtually brand new although it does look a bit worn - this is because I had soaked it in water in an attempt (as directed by Galco) to mold the fit to the gun (wrapped gun in a plastic "baggie" to keep it dry) and then put it in holster long enough for the leather to dry. This resulted in the slightly worn look.This pistol comes with an extra magazine. I have one set up for FMJ range ammo, and the other for hollow point self defense ammo. This is supposed to prevent "rim lock", but I'm not sure if it's necessary or not. The "rim lock" kit easily converts from the longer cartridges to the slightly shorter HP ammo so either can be used either way. Just requires sliding a thin metal bar out of the magazine by moving the base plate a fraction of an inch and replacing it is just the opposite. Takes just a few seconds. Kel Tec no longer sells these rim-lock kits, so I would guess they may have never been necessary if the magazines are correctly loaded (as per the included instructions). I have used hollow points without the rim-lock kit (which is what it's intended for) along with the flat nose Winchester FMJ ammo sold at Walmart, (same length as most hollow point ammo) and I've never experienced rim-lock when firing. I also am including a box of the Power Point ammo and the super high velocity RBCD ammo. (both boxes were about $40 for 20 rounds each, so not what I'd ever use for range ammo. Both these rounds have the same profile as regular FMJ ammo, so even is rim-lock were a real issue, it would not affect either of these high dollar cartridges.The hard chrome plating is amazing....ever single stell part is hard chromed down to the take-down pin and I believe even the internal springs. I've had this gun for several years and there's never ever been a trace rust or any kind of corrosion. The actual frame is aluminum (covered with a polymer grip) so the slide is hard chromed steel riding on aluminum rails which eliminates any chance of galling. I lived blocks from the ocean and even the very "salty" air has not affected the gun in any way (same for the sweat in my pockets) - I've never had a single failure to feed or to fire  or to extract. Gun has been 100% reliable. And while some may think the .32acp is not a powerful enough round for self defense, I disagree since at it's intended range (like for a street mugging, etc.) - it's more than enough to stop any threat (the .32 is still commonly used by police forces in Europe).

title: For Sale:  CUSTOM handmade ghillie suit
postcontent: Army Sniper qualified, SDM qualified, built from experience. If intriuged i will verify credentials only if youre interested in a sale. While creating this build i incorporated everything i found useful while in the course and added things i wish i would have had at the time and while in service. Ive had troubles getting my emails to go through in order to respond. If your interested leave your number in email and I will text you rather than email response . thank you Ghillie specsBuilt on a Medium Regular multicam Fire resistant base uniformThe netting on the back of both the pants and blouse is sewn on and additionally reinforced with a rubber like glue to ensure it will not rip when crawling in the prone.The entire backing is coated with the previously mentioned netting and is the attachment point for the strands of jute. In between the strands of jute i have strategically placed strands of fire sealed 550 cord to attach natural foliage clipped from the area in which you are operating.I had cut sections of duffle bag (canvas) and sewn the section on the front portion of the blouse and pants to reinforce the structural integrity of the uniform while crawling in the prone. The sewing on the front is reinforced with rubber glue as well. The canvas on the front was then coated with several coats of paint in different patterns and sizes to create depth in order to give the uniform a greater camouflaging ability when viewed from the front. The back of the blouse has a vent cut into it in order to release built up heat. The seam was then sewn around to give it strength. the vent is also covered with a 2nd layer of netting.The veil (boonie with jute) is also covered in the same netting and jute used on the blouse and pants and is attached to the boonie by zip ties. The ghillie itself is virgin, new, unused, and has not been mud washed. Prior to use, in the area of operation, you would find a mud pit, swamp, ect ect, and roll the uniform in it in order to match the color of the jute to the color of the earth. There are many factors that go into effective camouflaging if you are interested in purchasing the ghillie i would have no problem sharing some information with you on the proper use of the ghillie and additionally give you the information needed to make the ghillie as effective as possible. Any questions feel free to ask.  My intent is to sell the suit in order to fund other projects. If you have a special request or would like a custom suit built feel free to contact me. Additionally, I will not give you the time of day if you message me with the intent of giving me tips and tricks. Im aware of other styles of suits and have built many in different forms, however if you have a professional bit of information to share feel free. thanks all for your time.
